Problem statement:¶

| Description of fnlwgt (final weight)
|
| The weights on the CPS files are controlled to independent estimates of the
| civilian noninstitutional population of the US.  These are prepared monthly
| for us by Population Division here at the Census Bureau.  We use 3 sets of
| controls.
|  These are:
|          1.  A single cell estimate of the population 16+ for each state.
|          2.  Controls for Hispanic Origin by age and sex.
|          3.  Controls by Race, age and sex.
|
| We use all three sets of controls in our weighting program and "rake" through
| them 6 times so that by the end we come back to all the controls we used.
|
| The term estimate refers to population totals derived from CPS by creating
| "weighted tallies" of any specified socio-economic characteristics of the
| population.
|
| People with similar demographic characteristics should have
| similar weights.  There is one important caveat to remember
| about this statement.  That is that since the CPS sample is
| actually a collection of 51 state samples, each with its own
| probability of selection, the statement only applies within
| state.

Rename column names¶

We can see that there are 32561 instances and 15 features in the data set.

In the dataset description, it is given that there are 14 attributes and 1 Class which is the target variable. So, we have 14 attributes and 1 target variable.

As there are no attributes names it looks meaningless. Lets assign names to attibutes.

We can see that the dataset does not have proper column names. The columns are merely labelled as 0,1,2.... and so on. We should give proper names to the columns. I will do it as follows:-

In [12]:
cols = ['age','workclass','fnlwgt','education','education-num','marital-status','occupation','relationship','race','sex','capital-gain','capital-loss','hours-per-week','native-country','income']

adult.columns = cols

We have null values in 'workclass','occupation','native-country' with nan values. Lets replace missing values with mode as variables are categorical.

In [32]:
# Identify categorical columns with missing values
categorical_columns_with_missing = ["workclass", "occupation", "native-country"]

# Replace missing values in categorical columns with the mode
for col in categorical_columns_with_missing:
    mode_value = adult[col].mode()[0]  # Calculate the mode
    adult[col].fillna(mode_value, inplace=True)

The k-Nearest Neighbors (kNN) algorithm is not inherently robust to outliers. In fact, kNN is often sensitive to outliers, as it relies on the distances between data points to make predictions. Outliers are data points that deviate significantly from the rest of the data and can distort the distance calculations, leading to inaccurate predictions.

capital-gain, capital-loss have outliers

Label encoding involves assigning a unique integer to each category in a categorical column. It's suitable when the categories have an ordinal relationship (e.g., "low," "medium," "high").

In [38]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Identify the categorical column to be encoded
categorical_column = "workclass"  

# Initialize the LabelEncoder
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()

# Fit and transform the column with label encoding
adult[categorical_column] = label_encoder.fit_transform(adult[categorical_column])

# Now the categorical column has been converted to numerical format
